Pour the @water{220%ml} for the bulgur into a large #saucepan{}. Stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}. Stir the @dried cranberries{30%g} into the bulgur, pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat.

Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large frying pan on medium-high heat. Drain the @king prawns{225%g}.

Once hot, add the prawns and stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw prawns.

While the prawns cook, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a garlic press).

In a large #bowl{}, combine the @red wine vinegar{12%ml}, @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} for the dressing and a good pinch of @?sugar{pinch} (if you'd like).

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Leave your dressing aside for now.

Stir the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and @harissa paste{50%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) into the prawns and cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @water{100%ml} for the sauce and the remaining veg stock paste. Add a pinch of @?sugar{pinch} (if you'd like).

Stir and bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Cook so the prawns are opaque in the middle.

Once thickened, stir the @baby spinach{40%g} into the prawn pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

When ready, fluff up the bulgur with a #fork{}. Spoon half of the dressing over the bulgur and stir through.

Toss the @baby leaf mix{20%g} through the remaining dressing.

> TIP: Don't add the leaves too early or they'll go soggy.

Share the cranberry bulgur between your bowls.

Spoon the harissa prawns and spinach over the top.

Serve the dressed baby leaf salad alongside. Enjoy!